Published: 16:16 January 11, 2018 
Reuters

Dublin: A vast majority of Irish men believe abortion should only be allowed in cases of rape or incest or a serious risk to the mother’s life, but they back the woman’s right to decide whether to continue or end her pregnancy, a study showed on Thursday.

The nationwide poll of 3,000 adults, which comes before a national referendum on May 25 to liberalise what is one of the world’s strictest abortion laws, said 71 per cent of Irish men opposed the termination of an pregnancy in cases of fatal foetal abnormalities. However, 61 per cent said the woman should have a final say over the termination or continuation of the pregnancy regardless of the reasons for seeking one.

Some 49 per cent of men in the survey said abortion is morally wrong. Nationwide, the survey, conducted by Ipsos/MRBI, found 43 per cent of Ireland’s men and women define abortion as morally wrong, 12 per cent say it is morally acceptable but not morally right, 27 per cent said it is morally neutral and the remaining 18 per cent said they did not know.
